		{
			"id": 1,
			"parent": 2,
			"text": "Bidirectional models of word alignment are an appealing alternative to post-hoc combinations of directional word aligners . <S>\r",
			"relation": "contrast"
		},
		{
			"id": 2,
			"parent": 4,
			"text": "Unfortunately , most bidirectional formulations are NP-Hard to solve , \r",
			"relation": "bg-compare"
		},
		{
			"id": 3,
			"parent": 2,
			"text": "and a previous attempt to use a relaxation-based decoder yielded few exact solutions ( 6 % ) . <S>\r",
			"relation": "joint"
		},
		{
			"id": 4,
			"parent": 0,
			"text": "We present a novel relaxation \r",
			"relation": "ROOT"
		},
		{
			"id": 5,
			"parent": 4,
			"text": "for decoding the bidirectional model of DeNero and Macherey ( 2011 ) . <S>\r",
			"relation": "elab-addition"
		},
		{
			"id": 6,
			"parent": 4,
			"text": "The relaxation can be solved with a modified version of the Viterbi algorithm . <S>\r",
			"relation": "elab-addition"
		},
		{
			"id": 7,
			"parent": 8,
			"text": "To find optimal solutions on difficult instances , \r",
			"relation": "enablement"
		},
		{
			"id": 8,
			"parent": 4,
			"text": "we alternate between incrementally adding constraints and applying optimality-preserving coarse-to-fine pruning . <S>\r",
			"relation": "elab-addition"
		},
		{
			"id": 9,
			"parent": 4,
			"text": "The algorithm finds provably exact solutions on 86 % of sentence pairs \r",
			"relation": "evaluation"
		},
		{
			"id": 10,
